
"""
Answer 1: Linear interpolation gets the 'gist' right if we have about at minimum 4 samples per period, though this captures the overall amplitude properly only if samples happen to fall at the peak or trough of the signal. But if the sampling did not align with the start of a period, we would not end up capturing the peak-to-peak amplitude with linear interpolation. In practice you often want something like 8-10+ samples per period to have a good linear interpolation regardless of phase, though we will soon see that this is not the most important consideration.

Answer 2: One intuition that you might have is that you might need 2 samples (one for each peak) to capture the peak-to-peak properly for each period. This gets to the correct answer that we need the sampling frequency to be greater than twice the signal frequency (i.e., f_s > 2 * f_signal), but the reasoning behind why isn't actually about catching peaks. It turns out that any set of samples taken above this rate, landing wherever they happen to fall in the cycle, peaks or not, contains enough information to reconstruct the original signal perfectly, using an appropriate reconstruction method (more on this later). So you don't need to be lucky enough to sample exactly at the peaks; the guarantee holds regardless of where your samples land.

Answer 3: We could draw infinitely many plausible signals if the signal's frequency (or shape) is allowed to change between the sampled points — if we let the signal do anything it wants in the gaps, there are endless ways to connect the dots. Even if we restrict ourselves to the space of fixed-frequency sine waves, there can still be multiple different frequencies that produce the exact same samples — unless we already know the sampling frequency is fast enough relative to that frequency. Without that extra knowledge, the samples alone don't pin down a unique answer. More on this later when we visit Aliasing and the Nyquist theorem.
""";